00:02:51.761 --> 00:02:54.097
to accessibility education.

00:02:54.630 --> 00:02:56.064
I'm Olivia Richter.

00:02:56.065 --> 00:03:01.136
I have a brown pixie cut,
I wear glasses, and a black shirt.

00:03:01.137 --> 00:03:03.605
I'm a WordPress web designer by day,

00:03:03.606 --> 00:03:06.575
and an accessibility
advocate by passion.

00:03:06.576 --> 00:03:08.744
My job is building
inclusive websites,

00:03:08.745 --> 00:03:11.213
but my superpower
is learning new things,

00:03:11.214 --> 00:03:13.749
and getting lost in side quests.

00:03:13.750 --> 00:03:16.985
The last part is probably
how I ended up here.

00:03:16.986 --> 00:03:18.687
Not necessarily to teach you,

00:03:18.688 --> 00:03:22.124
but to take you through my journey
of getting people on board

00:03:22.125 --> 00:03:24.356
with digital accessibility.

00:03:24.961 --> 00:03:27.596
See, here's the thing I've learned.

00:03:27.597 --> 00:03:30.132
We all say we care about inclusion,

00:03:30.133 --> 00:03:33.135
but getting people to act on it,

00:03:33.136 --> 00:03:36.138
that's where
the real adventure begins.

00:03:36.139 --> 00:03:38.701
Let's start from the beginning.

00:03:40.810 --> 00:03:43.545
People create digital experiences.

00:03:43.546 --> 00:03:48.216
I know, incredibly insightful,
but if you really think about it,

00:03:48.217 --> 00:03:49.706
that is where the issue

00:03:49.707 --> 00:03:53.321
of inaccessible
experiences has its root.

00:03:53.322 --> 00:03:57.526
Most of those people never
face the barriers they create.

00:03:57.527 --> 00:04:01.229
They are like chefs
who don't taste their own food,

00:04:01.230 --> 00:04:04.599
serving up dishes
that poison some of the diners,

00:04:04.600 --> 00:04:07.302
and they don't even realize it.

00:04:07.303 --> 00:04:08.336
Why?

00:04:08.337 --> 00:04:11.606
Because when you can glide
through a website with a mouse,

00:04:11.607 --> 00:04:14.876
why would you question
a broken tab border?

00:04:14.877 --> 00:04:19.637
When you can see colors perfectly,
why stress about contrast?

00:04:19.816 --> 00:04:22.450
Exclusion isn't malice, mostly.

00:04:22.451 --> 00:04:24.765
It's ignorance on autopilot.

00:04:28.457 --> 00:04:30.992
We call this issue the empathy gap,

00:04:30.993 --> 00:04:33.461
an inability for people to empathize

00:04:33.462 --> 00:04:35.463
with others, in this case people

00:04:35.464 --> 00:04:38.066
with disabilities,
leading them to ignore

00:04:38.067 --> 00:04:41.875
the barriers that disabled
people face every day,

00:04:42.471 --> 00:04:44.739
but let's call it what it is.

00:04:44.740 --> 00:04:49.178
Most people don't give
a damn until it happens to them.

00:04:49.579 --> 00:04:53.014
Disability is the thought of,
"It won't be me."

00:04:53.015 --> 00:04:55.318
Until, of course, it is.

00:04:55.618 --> 00:04:59.855
Broken arms, aging eyes,
situational limits,

00:04:59.856 --> 00:05:02.425
or getting into a car accident.

00:05:02.558 --> 00:05:06.128
Disability is the world's
most inclusive club.

00:05:09.465 --> 00:05:12.300
How do we close the empathy gap?

00:05:12.301 --> 00:05:15.470
How do we get every developer,
every designer,

00:05:15.471 --> 00:05:18.240
every editor to create
while having people

00:05:18.241 --> 00:05:20.342
with disabilities in mind?

00:05:20.343 --> 00:05:22.612
Well, it's complicated.

00:05:24.447 --> 00:05:27.949
A common way we try to get
people to empathize with people

00:05:27.950 --> 00:05:32.472
with disabilities, is to simulate
the disability for them.

00:05:32.788 --> 00:05:36.992
This can look something
like using a wheelchair for an hour,

00:05:36.993 --> 00:05:40.881
or you blindfold yourself
to simulate being blind.

00:05:40.963 --> 00:05:44.216
Think about these
blindfolded trust walks,

00:05:44.367 --> 00:05:47.469
or using earplugs
where you simulate being hard

00:05:47.470 --> 00:05:49.472
of hearing or deaf.

00:05:50.406 --> 00:05:53.299
Let me give you a personal example.

00:05:54.510 --> 00:05:57.379
I visited this museum
in the Netherlands,

00:05:57.380 --> 00:05:59.579
the Muzieum in Nijmegen,

00:05:59.580 --> 00:06:03.686
where they take you on a tour
in complete darkness.

00:06:04.320 --> 00:06:05.787
Unlike in this picture here,

00:06:05.788 --> 00:06:08.690
where you can rarely
see a chair and the floor,

00:06:08.691 --> 00:06:10.927
it was completely dark.

00:06:11.093 --> 00:06:12.661
You're led by a guide you meet

00:06:12.662 --> 00:06:16.197
in the darkness, so,
you can't see them.

00:06:16.198 --> 00:06:17.632
They don't see you either.

00:06:17.633 --> 00:06:19.601
Not just because of the darkness,

00:06:19.602 --> 00:06:22.404
but because they're visually
impaired.

00:06:22.405 --> 00:06:25.407
In the dark,
you're navigating everyday spaces.

00:06:25.408 --> 00:06:29.644
Like a home, you cross a street,
and you end up in a bar.

00:06:29.645 --> 00:06:32.415
All without relying on sight.

00:06:32.581 --> 00:06:34.410
While enjoying your drink,

00:06:34.411 --> 00:06:38.788
your guide asks
you what you think they look like.

00:06:39.055 --> 00:06:42.546
I have to say,
it was incredibly eye-opening.

00:06:43.426 --> 00:06:45.360
While it was just a brief experience

00:06:45.361 --> 00:06:48.063
for me, the real purpose hits home.

00:06:48.064 --> 00:06:50.532
The simulation
of blindness can help people

00:06:50.533 --> 00:06:55.037
with degenerative vision
prepare for the future.

00:06:55.471 --> 00:06:59.914
Imagine training your other senses
to handle daily tasks.

00:07:02.378 --> 00:07:05.023
Here's a simulation of dyslexia.

00:07:05.281 --> 00:07:10.041
The letters in the text change
places, and it's hard to read.

00:07:10.152 --> 00:07:13.154
It's a great reminder
that what seems simple to you,

00:07:13.155 --> 00:07:14.622
can be a real challenge

00:07:14.623 --> 00:07:18.511
when your brain processes
information differently.

00:07:19.595 --> 00:07:23.099
With all that said, does it work?

00:07:23.232 --> 00:07:25.467
Does simulating
the experience of people

00:07:25.468 --> 00:07:29.371
with disabilities work to get
non-disabled people to create

00:07:29.372 --> 00:07:31.686
more accessible experiences?

00:07:32.441 --> 00:07:33.809
It depends.

00:07:34.744 --> 00:07:37.812
Targeted simulations
can be surprisingly effective

00:07:37.813 --> 00:07:41.304
when used like a spotlight,
not a floodlight.

00:07:41.884 --> 00:07:45.153
You need to show
why color contrast matters.

00:07:45.154 --> 00:07:47.255
A quick color blindness
simulation slaps

00:07:47.256 --> 00:07:49.391
the designer with an, "Oh wow,

00:07:49.392 --> 00:07:52.527
I literally can't read that moment."

00:07:52.528 --> 00:07:54.759
No guideline can replicate.

00:07:55.431 --> 00:07:58.099
Here, we have such
a simulation of green

00:07:58.100 --> 00:08:00.935
blindness with a yellow
forest in the background,

00:08:00.936 --> 00:08:05.975
and text in the foreground that,
well, I can't read.

00:08:06.442 --> 00:08:07.981
Also, the same simulation

00:08:07.982 --> 00:08:11.790
with complete color
blindness in black and white,

00:08:12.715 --> 00:08:16.365
and this is the picture
without the simulation.

00:08:17.019 --> 00:08:18.720
The forest stays yellow,

00:08:18.721 --> 00:08:22.257
but you have red text
on top of it that reads,

00:08:22.258 --> 00:08:24.060
"Can you read that?"

00:08:24.260 --> 00:08:28.597
It's not a great contrast,
but that's the whole point.

00:08:29.565 --> 00:08:32.944
While simulations
like blindfolding sometimes stick

00:08:32.945 --> 00:08:36.538
where theory fails,
there are a few reasons.

00:08:36.539 --> 00:08:38.874
First, they're visceral.

00:08:38.908 --> 00:08:41.509
They expose hidden design flaws,

00:08:41.510 --> 00:08:44.237
and they make barriers feel real.

00:08:44.380 --> 00:08:46.748
Nothing makes a manager prioritize

00:08:46.749 --> 00:08:51.033
accessibility like struggling
to use their own product,

00:08:51.187 --> 00:08:53.988
but there are a lot of limitations.

00:08:53.989 --> 00:08:56.303
Let's get into some of them.

00:08:57.293 --> 00:09:00.229
Disabilities aren't
one-size-fits-all.

00:09:00.596 --> 00:09:03.331
We need to acknowledge
that disabilities,

00:09:03.332 --> 00:09:06.801
even specific diagnosis,
do not always cause

00:09:06.802 --> 00:09:10.372
the same experience
for every affected person.

00:09:10.606 --> 00:09:12.941
You can see two different simulations

00:09:12.942 --> 00:09:15.810
of diabetic retinopathy here.

00:09:15.811 --> 00:09:18.947
There are different dark spots
in the field of view.

00:09:18.948 --> 00:09:21.797
On one, there are
smaller and more dots,

00:09:21.798 --> 00:09:25.353
and on the other one,
on the other simulation,

00:09:25.354 --> 00:09:29.825
there are a few bigger,
more irregular spots.

00:09:30.426 --> 00:09:32.760
This means that
the simulation can, at best,

00:09:32.761 --> 00:09:37.165
only simulate the temporary
experience of a specific person.

00:09:37.166 --> 00:09:41.450
More likely, it will simulate
the experience of no one.

00:09:42.271 --> 00:09:46.873
A temporary simulation
is not the same as lived experience.

00:09:47.042 --> 00:09:50.081
Spending an hour
in a wheelchair teaches you

00:09:50.082 --> 00:09:52.847
how to spend an hour in a wheelchair.

00:09:52.848 --> 00:09:56.818
What's missed is the exhaustion
of planning every route,

00:09:56.819 --> 00:09:59.654
the stairs, the broken elevator,

00:09:59.655 --> 00:10:03.054
the train and bus that can't
accommodate you at the moment,

00:10:03.055 --> 00:10:05.727
the plane crew
that destroys your wheelchair,

00:10:05.728 --> 00:10:08.696
the bureaucracy
with the healthcare system,

00:10:08.697 --> 00:10:12.347
and to tie it all together,
the discrimination.

00:10:13.636 --> 00:10:16.066
Even more,
if a disability is combined

00:10:16.067 --> 00:10:18.973
with factors such as race or class,

00:10:18.974 --> 00:10:22.311
intersectionality
plays additionally to it.

00:10:22.811 --> 00:10:25.130
Intersectionality is the intersection

00:10:25.131 --> 00:10:28.031
of multiple forms of discrimination.

00:10:30.653 --> 00:10:33.389
Simulations can distort reality.

00:10:33.789 --> 00:10:35.690
They can be misleading.

00:10:35.891 --> 00:10:37.225
You might think you know about

00:10:37.226 --> 00:10:39.661
the capabilities
of a disabled person,

00:10:39.662 --> 00:10:43.331
but you didn't train
and you don't have the context.

00:10:43.332 --> 00:10:46.100
This can lead to pity
for the disabled person,

00:10:46.101 --> 00:10:49.170
to frustration,
and the idea of incompetence,

00:10:49.171 --> 00:10:54.343
which does not reflect the experience
of people with disabilities.

00:10:55.044 --> 00:10:56.862
It can be patronizing.

00:11:00.249 --> 00:11:02.717
Simulations can reduce disabilities

00:11:02.718 --> 00:11:06.821
to stereotypes like,
"All blind people use Braille,"

00:11:06.822 --> 00:11:09.357
or more relevant to this talk,

00:11:09.358 --> 00:11:12.360
"All blind people
use a Screen Reader."

00:11:12.361 --> 00:11:14.997
This, of course, is not true.

00:11:15.965 --> 00:11:18.132
Another issue is the simple fact

00:11:18.133 --> 00:11:21.736
that some disabilities just
cannot be simulated in a way

00:11:21.737 --> 00:11:24.911
that even remotely
matches lived reality.

00:11:25.574 --> 00:11:27.809
Think about chronic pain.

00:11:27.810 --> 00:11:32.015
How do you simulate fatigue
that builds up over hours?

00:11:32.414 --> 00:11:34.148
Autistic sensory overload,

00:11:34.149 --> 00:11:37.853
which isn't just loud
noises equals to bad.

00:11:38.153 --> 00:11:40.755
Another example
is the loss of mobility,

00:11:40.756 --> 00:11:44.406
which can cause issues
with some input devices.

00:11:44.426 --> 00:11:48.296
Like in this picture where the person
has a prosthetic hand.

00:11:48.297 --> 00:11:51.633
People who are used to working
with a mouse can understand

00:11:51.634 --> 00:11:53.368
that some people need websites

00:11:53.369 --> 00:11:56.404
to work with a keyboard,
but too often

00:11:56.405 --> 00:11:58.740
that ends up being translated into,

00:11:58.741 --> 00:12:00.675
"Let's add a bunch of keyboard macros

00:12:00.676 --> 00:12:03.770
to make our app
usable with a keyboard."

00:12:03.979 --> 00:12:08.349
In reality, this approach
often causes even more issues,

00:12:08.350 --> 00:12:12.396
because the developer
didn't understand the problem.

00:12:12.421 --> 00:12:17.025
We run the risk of giving
designers ideas for fixes that do fix

00:12:17.026 --> 00:12:20.329
the barriers
for the simulated disability,

00:12:20.362 --> 00:12:22.032
but do little to improve

00:12:22.062 --> 00:12:25.360
the experience
of real disabled people.

00:12:25.868 --> 00:12:28.903
We end up training developers
and designers to design

00:12:28.904 --> 00:12:34.008
for simulations, not people,
and we waste time on fixes

00:12:34.009 --> 00:12:36.819
that can create even new barriers.

00:12:38.814 --> 00:12:42.650
We also need to address
the fact that simulated disabilities

00:12:42.651 --> 00:12:45.054
are a controversial topic.

00:12:45.354 --> 00:12:48.189
A simulated disability
is trying to portray

00:12:48.190 --> 00:12:49.724
the experience of people,

00:12:49.725 --> 00:12:54.089
but only portrays a very narrow
part of this experience,

00:12:54.096 --> 00:12:58.856
and it reduces lived experience
to a temporary inconvenience.

00:12:59.401 --> 00:13:02.970
Furthermore, the simulation
of a disability creates

00:13:02.971 --> 00:13:05.606
the perception that the problem

00:13:05.607 --> 00:13:08.309
is within the person
with a disability,

00:13:08.310 --> 00:13:12.447
and that we as creators
of digital spaces have to adapt

00:13:12.448 --> 00:13:15.017
our products to their needs.

00:13:15.984 --> 00:13:19.554
I would see parallels
to the medical model of disability,

00:13:19.555 --> 00:13:24.759
where disability is seen as something
that has to be cured, or corrected.

00:13:24.760 --> 00:13:27.595
The focus is on
the individual's impairment,

00:13:27.596 --> 00:13:30.323
rather than the system's failure.

00:13:30.599 --> 00:13:35.677
This model faces a lot of criticism
because of its ableist views,

00:13:35.804 --> 00:13:38.606
so we always need to contextualize

00:13:38.607 --> 00:13:40.616
these simulations with the knowledge

00:13:40.617 --> 00:13:42.410
that the barriers are the problem,

00:13:42.411 --> 00:13:44.812
not the disabilities, and especially,

00:13:44.813 --> 00:13:47.749
not the people with the disabilities.

00:13:49.184 --> 00:13:51.619
Then, there's the ethical question.

00:13:51.620 --> 00:13:53.654
Is it appropriate for someone

00:13:53.655 --> 00:13:57.725
without a disability
to pretend to have one,

00:13:57.726 --> 00:14:00.596
even for educational purposes?

00:14:01.130 --> 00:14:03.398
Some argue
that it can feel dismissive,

00:14:03.399 --> 00:14:06.567
or even exploitative,
especially when it's done

00:14:06.568 --> 00:14:10.297
without the input
from the disability community.

00:14:10.339 --> 00:14:12.507
The uncomfortable truth is,

00:14:12.508 --> 00:14:16.078
simulations can feel
like disability cosplay.

00:14:19.548 --> 00:14:22.583
People may gain some empathy
through a simulation,

00:14:22.584 --> 00:14:25.820
but is this empathy
really directed towards

00:14:25.821 --> 00:14:28.383
the person with the disability?

00:14:28.557 --> 00:14:33.061
Maybe, but often in a pitiful way,
and not empowering.

00:14:34.096 --> 00:14:35.129
In most cases,

00:14:35.130 --> 00:14:39.367
this empathy is more likely
directed at the perceived reality

00:14:39.368 --> 00:14:44.038
of the simulation, and often
ends up solving the wrong problem.

00:14:44.039 --> 00:14:48.509
To summarize, critics argue
this empathy is short-lived,

00:14:48.510 --> 00:14:51.345
and doesn't equate
to lived experience.

00:14:51.346 --> 00:14:56.106
You might prioritize temporary
fixes over systemic inclusion.

00:14:56.452 --> 00:15:00.154
These simulations can reinforce
the medical model thinking,

00:15:00.155 --> 00:15:03.646
where disability is seen
as a problem to fix.

00:15:04.793 --> 00:15:06.994
I want to empathize that I do think

00:15:06.995 --> 00:15:08.963
that simulations can have merits,

00:15:08.964 --> 00:15:12.455
and can be very useful
in some circumstances,

00:15:13.135 --> 00:15:17.772
but clearly, simulating
a disability to encourage empathy

00:15:17.773 --> 00:15:21.309
is not a catch-all solution
to the complex topic

00:15:21.310 --> 00:15:26.648
of accessibility advocacy,
so, what is?

00:15:29.885 --> 00:15:32.620
The real answer to the empathy gap

00:15:32.621 --> 00:15:35.795
is listening to people
with disabilities.

00:15:35.958 --> 00:15:37.993
Plain and simple.

00:15:38.126 --> 00:15:39.994
It's about listening, learning,

00:15:39.995 --> 00:15:45.267
and committing to creating
experiences that work for everyone.

00:15:46.201 --> 00:15:47.935
The empathy gap doesn't close

00:15:47.936 --> 00:15:51.073
through simulations,
pity, or guesswork.

00:15:51.206 --> 00:15:54.309
It closes when we shut up and listen.

00:15:55.210 --> 00:15:56.310
At the end of the day,

00:15:56.311 --> 00:15:59.981
accessibility isn't about
assuming what works.

00:15:59.982 --> 00:16:02.083
It's about centering disabled voices

00:16:02.084 --> 00:16:05.496
in design, development,
and decision-making.

00:16:06.221 --> 00:16:07.955
This is shown and shown again.

00:16:07.956 --> 00:16:10.435
Accessibility improves
when designers,

00:16:10.436 --> 00:16:14.362
developers, creators,
managers, and everyone else

00:16:14.363 --> 00:16:17.765
involved in the process
of creating digital experiences,

00:16:17.766 --> 00:16:20.635
has direct conversations
with disabled people,

00:16:20.636 --> 00:16:23.639
and actually listens to them.

00:16:25.541 --> 00:16:29.310
This works so well, because,
as people, we can empathize

00:16:29.311 --> 00:16:32.813
really well with the people
we meet in our real lives.

00:16:32.814 --> 00:16:34.582
We understand their experience much

00:16:34.583 --> 00:16:38.452
better if we see how they interact
with our products.

00:16:38.453 --> 00:16:42.023
There is no real replacement
for this process.

00:16:42.658 --> 00:16:44.659
Watching a screen
reader user struggle

00:16:44.660 --> 00:16:47.495
with your intuitive UI is much

00:16:47.496 --> 00:16:50.987
more eye-opening than
any blindfold exercise.

00:16:53.268 --> 00:16:57.071
This approach also comes
with plenty of other benefits,

00:16:57.072 --> 00:17:01.342
including but not limited
to more diverse viewpoints,

00:17:01.343 --> 00:17:05.213
and product teams,
increased adaptability,

00:17:05.581 --> 00:17:08.849
higher employee
retention and satisfaction,

00:17:08.850 --> 00:17:11.786
better company culture,
and many more.

00:17:12.554 --> 00:17:16.045
When disabled people
are part of the process,

00:17:16.124 --> 00:17:18.993
designs are stress-tested early,
you don't get

00:17:18.994 --> 00:17:22.029
these last-minute
accessibility patches,

00:17:22.030 --> 00:17:25.766
innovation thrives,
and everyone wins.

00:17:25.767 --> 00:17:27.468
Think about the curb cut effect,

00:17:27.469 --> 00:17:29.770
where curb cuts
were invented for wheelchairs,

00:17:29.771 --> 00:17:32.473
but now everyone uses them.

00:17:32.474 --> 00:17:36.110
For example, if you use a stroller,
a bike, a trolley,

00:17:36.111 --> 00:17:38.714
or your transport-heavy stuff.

00:17:41.216 --> 00:17:46.021
Our goal is to normalize
accessibility as a core skill,

00:17:46.121 --> 00:17:50.458
not a niche checklist,
and never ever assume you know

00:17:50.459 --> 00:17:53.871
better than the people
you're designing for.

00:17:55.497 --> 00:17:57.431
A lot of people hear this, and think

00:17:57.432 --> 00:18:00.968
that I am suggesting
that they should need to add people

00:18:00.969 --> 00:18:04.305
with disabilities to their quality
assurance pipeline,

00:18:04.306 --> 00:18:06.407
and they absolutely should,

00:18:06.408 --> 00:18:09.577
but this is not just
what I am saying.

00:18:09.578 --> 00:18:14.100
People with disabilities
should be involved in every step.

00:18:14.249 --> 00:18:16.317
They should be involved in every step

00:18:16.318 --> 00:18:19.421
of the way towards the final product.

00:18:20.989 --> 00:18:25.092
This solution is not as easy
to implement as it sounds.

00:18:25.093 --> 00:18:28.896
Hiring disabled talent
isn't as simple as posting a job ad,

00:18:28.897 --> 00:18:31.542
and waiting for magic to happen.

00:18:31.633 --> 00:18:34.268
We have the perfect candidate trap.

00:18:34.269 --> 00:18:38.472
The problem is,
companies want unicorns, for example,

00:18:38.473 --> 00:18:43.077
a senior React developer
who is also an accessibility expert,

00:18:43.078 --> 00:18:45.247
and has lived experience.

00:18:45.681 --> 00:18:49.250
The reality is,
you don't need a disability hire.

00:18:49.251 --> 00:18:53.059
You need great talent
who happens to be disabled.

00:18:53.822 --> 00:18:55.723
The awareness gap.

00:18:55.724 --> 00:18:57.958
Many companies don't even realize

00:18:57.959 --> 00:19:00.594
that their product,
or website is inaccessible,

00:19:00.595 --> 00:19:04.562
and that they should hire
people with disabilities.

00:19:05.567 --> 00:19:07.735
The accessibility paradox.

00:19:07.736 --> 00:19:10.706
Career pages are often inaccessible.

00:19:11.139 --> 00:19:14.241
The irony is,
that companies often say,

00:19:14.242 --> 00:19:16.677
"We can't hire
people with disabilities

00:19:16.678 --> 00:19:19.647
until we fix our site,
which we need people

00:19:19.648 --> 00:19:22.127
with disabilities to help fix.

00:19:22.651 --> 00:19:27.254
Yes, this takes time and work,
but guess what?

00:19:27.255 --> 00:19:29.604
So does retrofitting accessibility

00:19:29.605 --> 00:19:32.937
after you've built
an exclusionary product.

00:19:33.562 --> 00:19:37.846
You can't build products
for people you refuse to hire.

00:19:38.200 --> 00:19:40.234
This isn't about charity hiring.

00:19:40.235 --> 00:19:43.804
It's about closing the empathy
gap where it matters most.

00:19:43.805 --> 00:19:45.507
Your payroll.

00:19:47.609 --> 00:19:50.377
With all these problems in mind,
