00:23:36.237 --> 00:23:39.440
We could apply a filter
to a website to simulate

00:23:39.441 --> 00:23:41.838
the loss of color perception.

00:23:41.943 --> 00:23:45.879
If we try to apply our technique
of simulating a barrier instead

00:23:45.880 --> 00:23:49.116
of a disability,
we very quickly realize

00:23:49.117 --> 00:23:52.608
that it just doesn't work
for this situation.

00:23:52.954 --> 00:23:54.288
We can't take the website,

00:23:54.289 --> 00:23:58.225
and change it in a way to add
barriers, or to make it seem

00:23:58.226 --> 00:24:01.955
like it wasn't designed
for non-disabled people.

00:24:02.597 --> 00:24:05.106
Simulating barriers
isn't a replacement

00:24:05.107 --> 00:24:07.256
for disabled perspectives.

00:24:07.335 --> 00:24:09.737
It's a bridge to get
teams to care enough

00:24:09.738 --> 00:24:11.969
to seek those perspectives.

00:24:13.041 --> 00:24:15.042
We are not here to mimic struggle.

00:24:15.043 --> 00:24:20.849
We are here to destroy unnecessary
struggle at its source, bad design.

00:24:23.585 --> 00:24:25.986
Earlier, we identified key problems

00:24:25.987 --> 00:24:28.856
with traditional disability
simulations.

00:24:28.857 --> 00:24:31.526
Now, let's compare the two.

00:24:32.093 --> 00:24:34.294
Simulating a disability often leads

00:24:34.295 --> 00:24:38.799
to fixes that don't actually
help real disabled users,

00:24:38.800 --> 00:24:41.568
because the simulation
is based on assumptions,

00:24:41.569 --> 00:24:43.438
not lived experience.

00:24:44.339 --> 00:24:45.939
Barrier simulations avoid this,

00:24:45.940 --> 00:24:50.244
because the problem
isn't tied to a specific disability.

00:24:50.245 --> 00:24:52.346
Instead of prompting a solution,

00:24:52.347 --> 00:24:54.882
it simply prompts us
to think about barriers

00:24:54.883 --> 00:24:57.819
and accessibility in a different way.

00:24:58.820 --> 00:25:02.390
The next big topic is,
of course, controversy.

00:25:02.424 --> 00:25:04.558
To be honest, I can't know for sure

00:25:04.559 --> 00:25:08.362
that this different approach
is free from controversy.

00:25:08.363 --> 00:25:11.732
There's a good argument
that we are still trying to simulate

00:25:11.733 --> 00:25:15.669
a part of lived experience
of people with disabilities

00:25:15.670 --> 00:25:20.034
in a way that simply does
not reflect the whole picture.

00:25:20.208 --> 00:25:22.676
I actually agree with this argument,

00:25:22.677 --> 00:25:24.545
which is why I will always insist

00:25:24.546 --> 00:25:27.581
that the only real solution
to the empathy gap

00:25:27.582 --> 00:25:29.883
is working with people
with disabilities,

00:25:29.884 --> 00:25:33.354
and actually listening to them.

00:25:34.589 --> 00:25:37.124
My reply is, therefore,
focused on why I think

00:25:37.125 --> 00:25:39.893
that simulating barriers
at least does not shift

00:25:39.894 --> 00:25:42.096
the focus to the disability.

00:25:42.097 --> 00:25:46.266
It does not center the person
with the disability as the problem.

00:25:46.267 --> 00:25:48.836
Instead, the attention
is directed towards

00:25:48.837 --> 00:25:52.906
the products we create,
and the barriers they contain.

00:25:52.907 --> 00:25:57.747
The focus stays on broken systems,
not individual impairments.

00:25:58.413 --> 00:26:01.982
This is why I think this approach
might be more useful to trigger

00:26:01.983 --> 00:26:04.952
the kind of thinking,
and consideration that we want

00:26:04.953 --> 00:26:07.889
to see from designers and developers.

00:26:08.590 --> 00:26:11.959
This isn't about walking
in someone else's shoes.

00:26:11.960 --> 00:26:15.362
It's about realizing the shoes
we've designed are terrible,

00:26:15.363 --> 00:26:18.466
and demanding
better ones for everyone.

00:26:20.535 --> 00:26:23.036
With that said,
my personal conclusion

00:26:23.037 --> 00:26:24.638
is that these two concepts

00:26:24.639 --> 00:26:28.923
can be very useful if applied
to the correct situation.

00:26:29.177 --> 00:26:32.070
They serve very different purposes.

00:26:32.113 --> 00:26:35.482
If you want to highlight
a specific accessibility issue,

00:26:35.483 --> 00:26:38.952
a simulated disability
might be very helpful to improve

00:26:38.953 --> 00:26:43.257
the understanding for both technical,
and non-technical people.

00:26:43.258 --> 00:26:45.826
If you want to achieve
a more general mindset

00:26:45.827 --> 00:26:49.062
shift towards thinking
about the barriers we create,

00:26:49.063 --> 00:26:51.064
and provoke conversations and further

00:26:51.065 --> 00:26:53.667
interest in the topic
of accessibility,

00:26:53.668 --> 00:26:56.036
an experience with simulated barriers

00:26:56.037 --> 00:26:58.351
could be much more powerful.

00:27:00.475 --> 00:27:04.521
This realization left me
with a practical challenge.

00:27:04.846 --> 00:27:08.749
How do we turn this concept
into an actual experience

00:27:08.750 --> 00:27:10.852
that serves its purpose,

00:27:11.352 --> 00:27:14.446
and where can I find
simulated barriers?

00:27:14.589 --> 00:27:17.725
At first,
I didn't have a clear answer.

00:27:18.126 --> 00:27:19.893
Which is why I decided to start

00:27:19.894 --> 00:27:23.998
building some simulated barriers,
and go from there.

00:27:24.599 --> 00:27:26.401
Here was the problem.

00:27:26.801 --> 00:27:29.770
It's surprisingly hard
to create meaningful barriers

00:27:29.771 --> 00:27:33.074
for non-disabled users
in digital spaces.

00:27:33.408 --> 00:27:36.076
I can't change
their physical capabilities,

00:27:36.077 --> 00:27:39.780
but I can change
how they interact with my designs.

00:27:39.781 --> 00:27:42.115
The solution became clear.

00:27:42.116 --> 00:27:45.065
I needed to use assistive
technologies themselves

00:27:45.066 --> 00:27:46.688
as the barriers.

00:27:46.988 --> 00:27:49.056
My approach focused on web design,

00:27:49.057 --> 00:27:52.227
where many accessibility
failures occur.

00:27:52.694 --> 00:27:54.895
Most non-disabled people navigate

00:27:54.896 --> 00:27:57.898
effortlessly with a mouse
and clear visuals,

00:27:57.899 --> 00:28:01.628
but what if those tools
suddenly became useless?

00:28:02.637 --> 00:28:04.271
That became my goal.

00:28:04.272 --> 00:28:07.908
To create experiences
where traditional tools fail,

00:28:07.909 --> 00:28:12.035
forcing users to confront
digital barriers firsthand.

00:28:14.916 --> 00:28:18.252
With this in mind,
I came up with a list of requirements

00:28:18.253 --> 00:28:22.537
for a proof of concept
that I can use for this purpose.

