It should be easy to understand,

00:28:25.026 --> 00:28:28.696
short, engaging, and lastly, fun.

00:28:28.796 --> 00:28:33.501
I quickly go through my thought
process of each of these.

00:28:33.835 --> 00:28:35.570
Easy to understand.

00:28:35.903 --> 00:28:38.639
No jargon, no technical deep dives.

00:28:38.640 --> 00:28:43.143
It should just be a simple,
relatable digital interaction.

00:28:43.144 --> 00:28:45.412
The goal is that anyone who uses

00:28:45.413 --> 00:28:48.666
the internet for their job,
should get it.

00:28:48.816 --> 00:28:51.685
Short, this is not
a full training course,

00:28:51.686 --> 00:28:55.323
not a lecture,
just a short "aha" moment.

00:28:55.390 --> 00:28:58.925
Because this is the appetizer,
not the main course.

00:28:58.926 --> 00:29:03.607
It's meant to spark curiosity,
not to place deeper learning.

00:29:03.931 --> 00:29:06.333
It serves as a baseline
for conversations

00:29:06.334 --> 00:29:08.736
and more in-depth learning.

00:29:09.671 --> 00:29:10.872
Engaging.

00:29:11.039 --> 00:29:12.873
If you make the user do something,

00:29:12.874 --> 00:29:16.365
not just watch or read,
it is more memorable.

00:29:17.178 --> 00:29:18.379
Fun.

00:29:18.413 --> 00:29:21.411
The topic of fun
with this experience is something

00:29:21.412 --> 00:29:23.817
that I want to talk
a little bit deeper about

00:29:23.818 --> 00:29:26.187
because it is more nuanced.

00:29:29.357 --> 00:29:32.426
Fundamentally,
we are simulating an experience

00:29:32.427 --> 00:29:33.553
which is something

00:29:33.554 --> 00:29:36.229
that non-disabled people
are not used to.

00:29:36.230 --> 00:29:40.100
People with disabilities
are used to encountering barriers,

00:29:40.101 --> 00:29:45.639
and it is definitely not fun,
so it is reasonable to say

00:29:45.640 --> 00:29:49.209
that the simulation of barriers
should not be fun either,

00:29:49.210 --> 00:29:52.280
so why did I set this requirement?

00:29:53.448 --> 00:29:55.916
Fun is a powerful tool.

00:29:55.917 --> 00:29:57.719
It lowers defenses.

00:29:58.186 --> 00:30:01.988
People learn better when
they are not feeling attacked.

00:30:01.989 --> 00:30:04.192
It encourages exploration.

00:30:04.659 --> 00:30:06.326
If it's interesting, they'll poke

00:30:06.327 --> 00:30:09.129
around and discover more barriers.

00:30:09.130 --> 00:30:13.256
Playful experiences
are more memorable than dry ones.

00:30:13.701 --> 00:30:15.837
We reach more people.

00:30:16.471 --> 00:30:18.805
If the experience
is pure frustration,

00:30:18.806 --> 00:30:21.616
it leads to venting, not learning.

00:30:22.510 --> 00:30:26.380
Of course, this is a balance act,
because if we focus too much

00:30:26.381 --> 00:30:28.281
on making it a fun experience,

00:30:28.282 --> 00:30:30.183
the result
would be that we lose sight

00:30:30.184 --> 00:30:34.287
of the seriousness of the issue
we are trying to highlight.

00:30:34.288 --> 00:30:38.859
It's a balance act, and never
let the fun overshadow the point.

